# Technical Design — swiss-ephemeris-api

## Stack

- Python 3.12+, FastAPI, Pydantic v2, pysweph (community fork: `import swisseph as swe`)
- License: AGPL-3.0-or-later everywhere — source must always be public and match running code

## Architecture

```
core/swisseph_core.py      → SwissEphemerisCore (stateless, pure swisseph calls)
services/                   → SwissEphemerisCore for swisseph calls; business logic modules (zodiac, eclipses, lunar_phase, fixed_stars)
schemas/                    → Pydantic v2 models (request/response)
api/v1/endpoints/          → FastAPI route handlers (async def + asyncio.to_thread)
deps.py                     → FastAPI dependency injection (singleton)
```

## SwissEphemerisCore Rules

- All swisseph calls MUST go through `SwissEphemerisCore`
- `swisseph` is a C extension (sync/blocking) — NEVER call it directly in `async def` handlers
  → Use `asyncio.to_thread()` (Python 3.11+)
- **ONE-TIME only**: Call `swe.set_ephe_path()` once at app startup (e.g., in `main.py` lifespan). It is process-global — never call it per-request
- Never catch and suppress swisseph errors silently — raise descriptive FastAPI HTTPException

## swisseph Flag Constants (pysweph 2.10.3.6)

```
swe.FLG_SWIEPH   =   2  # Swiss Ephemeris (NOT 256!)
swe.FLG_SPEED    = 256  # include speed in result
swe.FLG_SIDEREAL = 65536  # tropical/sidereal toggle (NOT 768!)
swe.SIDBITS      = 256  # sidereal bit shift

# Sidereal mode: use FLG_SIDEREAL + SIDM_* (e.g. swe.FLG_SIDEREAL + swe.SIDM_LAHIRI)
# For tropical planets: swe.FLG_SWIEPH | swe.FLG_SPEED
# For sidereal planets: swe.FLG_SIDEREAL + sidm_constant + swe.FLG_SPEED
```

## Wrapper Scope (Comprehensive)

| Module | Coverage |
|---|---|
| Planets | Sun–Pluto, Chiron, Ceres, Pallas, Juno, Vesta, Earth |
| Lunar | North Node (TRUE/MEAN), South Node (derived as North + 180°), Lilith/Black Moon (via nod_aps_ut, apogee at index 3) |
| Special points | Part of Fortune (computed: ASC + Moon − Sun), Vertex, Anti-Vertex (derived: Vertex + 180°) |
| Fixed stars | 35 fixed stars (requires sefstars.txt in ephe path) |
| Houses | P(Placidus), K(Koch), W(Whole Sign), E(Equal), O(Porphyrius), R(Regiomontanus), C(Campanus), B(Alcabitius), M(Morinus) |
| Sidereal | All swisseph SIDM_* ayanamsa constants |
| Eclipses | Solar + Lunar (past and future) via swe.sol_eclipse_when_glob, swe.lun_eclipse_when |
| Lunar phases | Illumination % via swe.pheno_ut |

## API Design Rules

- All endpoints at `/api/v1/` prefix
- Input: `POST` with JSON body (Pydantic request model)
- Output: Pydantic response model with typed fields — never return raw dict
- Shared inputs go in `schemas/common.py` (`DateTimeInput`, `GeoLocation`)
- Use `Enum` for constrained values (planet names, house systems, signs)
- Response fields: `longitude`, `sign`, `degree_in_sign`, `speed`, `retrograde`, `house` (when applicable)
- Time: accept ISO 8601 string + timezone name; convert to Julian Day UT internally

## AGPL Compliance

- Root endpoint (`GET /`) MUST return project info, AGPL notice, and GitHub source URL
- Every public-facing response should include a `license` metadata field
- README must state: "Source code must always be public and match code running on server"
- No proprietary or NPML-licensed code may be added to this repository

## Error Handling

- Wrap all swisseph calls in try/except; raise `HTTPException(status_code=500, detail=...)`
- Use `ErrorResponse` schema for consistent error format: `{error, detail, code}`
- Never expose raw swisseph error codes to public API

## Naming Conventions

- `PlanetEnum` — uppercase enum members matching swe constants (e.g., `PlanetEnum.SUN = swe.SUN`)
- `HouseSystemEnum` — char codes: `P`, `K`, `W`, `E`, `O`, `R`, `C`, `B`, `M`
- All types: PascalCase (e.g., `PlanetPosition`, `HouseResponse`)
- All functions/methods: snake_case (e.g., `calc_planet`, `get_lunar_phase`)
- All environment variables: SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE

## Testing

- Use `pytest` + `pytest-asyncio`
- `conftest.py` provides fixtures for `SwissEphemerisCore` with temp ephe path
- Mock `swisseph` module for unit tests (test business logic, not C library)
- Integration tests call actual API endpoints with `TestClient`
